We make VISIOCITY available through the project page at https://visiocity.github.io/ and invite the researchers to test their algorithms on VISIOCITY benchmark.

Specically, the Vascular Modelling Toolkit vmtk software [98] ( http://www.vmtk.org ) together with a new meshing tool were used to perform such pre-processing phase.

All the ventricular LDRBMs (presented in Section 2), the novel atrial LDRBM (detailed in Section 3) and the numerical methods for the EP presented in Section 4 have been implemented within lifex(https: //lifex.gitlab.io/lifex ), a new in-house high-performance C++FE library mainly focused on cardiac applications based on deal.II FE core [105] ( https://www.dealii.org ).
To analyse the results we used ParaView (https://www.paraview.org ) an open-source, multi-platform data analysis and visualization application.

We constructed the idealized biventricular geometry using the prolate spheroid coordinate systems in the built-in CAD engine of gmsh , an open source 3D nite element mesh generator ( http://gmsh.info ), see Figure 7.

In order to obtain a smooth endocardium in both ventricles, we removed all the papillary muscles and the trabeculae carneae, using the CAD modeller SolidWorks (https://www.solidworks.com ) in combination with the software Meshmixer (http://www.meshmixer.com ), see Figure 9.
For each atrium, we created the corresponding triangular mesh using the constructive geometry module of Netgen (https://ngsolve.org ).
Afterwards, we treated the case of realistic left and right atria taken from the Zygote 3D heart model [94] and from the Riunet repository ( https://riunet.upv.es/handle/10251/55150 ).
